photos.notes: In front of the little rental home that we lived in with Mom in Marysville where she taught school for 1 year, before returning to Orcas for another year. This was a tiny little house about a block or two from the Reinell Boat Co. and the smell of cedar was always present. Ken would go over and pick up cedar scraps that were left on their burn pile. He built a rabbit hutch out of those scraps and mounted it in his bedroom window so that the rabbit could be both inside and outside - pretty cold in that bedroom. (Ken)

In 1885, Richard and Jane Willis homesteaded 149 acres near Obstruction Pass, between Doe Bay and Olga. Practically neighbors, the Richard Willis and George Culver families became well acquainted. Lack of mechanization made early farming an arduous task requiring more labor than was often available in one family. On certain occasions, such as harvest time, neighbors would team up and help one another. Other times it was necessary to hire help, and there were plenty of young men around who needed work. This photograph shows Cecil Willis, son of Richard Willis, who has been hired to help bring in the hay on Alderbrook Farm. The Culver's farmhouse is in the background.
photos.source: "Doe Bay History and Recipes" Cookbook. Photo courtesy of Durand family.

The groom's parents are on his right, and then the pastor. The flower girls in front include Evelyn and Leda Culver, ages 6 and 4, the daughters of O.H. and Mabel.
photos.description: Cecil Willis' presence on Alderbrook Farm brought him in contact with George and Diana Culver's daughter Emma Louise. Romance bloomed and on June 4, 1902, Cecil and Emma Louise were married. Pictured is the wedding party in front of the Alderbrook farmhouse; next to Reverend Dillon, are Richard and Jane Willis, parents of the groom. In the center are Cecil, the groom, and Emma, the bride. Second and third from the right are George and Diana Culver, parents of the bride. Fourth from the right is Otis Culver, brother of the bride. Far right is Otis' wife Mabel. Some of the guests were from Seattle and arrived by boat, docking at Kraft's Landing.
photos.source: "Doe Bay History and Recipes" Cookbook. Photo courtesy of Durand family.

photos.description: The Alderbrook farmhouse, built in 1889 for George and Diana Culver, Otis Culver's parents, became the grandest house on the east end of Orcas Island. The materials were barged from Bellingham to the Point Lawrence beach and carried to the site by horse-drawn wagon. The builders lived on the site during construction and were paid $1 per day plus board. The house and farm became the Culver's permanent residence. In 1894 Otis became the owner of the "Islander" newspaper in Friday Harbor, where he made his home. The Alderbrook farmhouse is owned by descendants of the Culver family, who have kept it in its original 1889 configuration. In 1985 it was listed on the National Register of Historic properties.
photos.source: "Doe Bay History and Recipes" Cookbook. Photo courtesy of Bob Patton.

photos.description: This 1954 photograph is of those initially responsible for the family tradition of preserving the Alderbrook farmhouse as it was built in 1889. Third from the left is Otis Culver's sister, Emma Louise Culver Willis. She was married to Cecil Willis of Obstruction Pass. The others are Otis and Mabel Culver's children. From the left are Leda (Culver) Hipkoe and Mary (Culver) Hall. Next to Emma are Florian (Culver) Johanson, Evelyn (Culver) Watson and Carroll Culver.
photos.source: "Doe Bay History and Recipes" Cookbook. Photo courtesy of Durand family.

photos.description: This photograph was taken circa 1935, when Point Lawrence Lodge opened. The first story of the lodge was built above the beach as an enclosed boathouse. The second story was the kitchen and guest dining room, and the upper level was devoted to the Culver family living quarters. The lodge was built by Carroll Culver with the help of E.J. Hilbert. The lumber was milled at the water-powered Thatcher Mill on Blakely Island. Hilbert went on to build and eventually own Sea Acres resort next door.
photos.source: "Doe Bay History and Recipes" Cookbook (Photo Courtesy of Bob Patton)
